<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-r6" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>R6</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        This chapter describes the R6 OOP system. R6 has two special properties:
      </p>

      <p><ul>
        <li><p>
          It uses the encapsulated OOP paradigm, which means that methods
          belong to objects, not generics, and you call them like
          <c>object$method()</c>.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          R6 objects are mutable, which means that they are modified in place,
          and hence have reference semantics.
        </p></li>
      </ul></p>

      <p>
        If you've learned OOP in another mainstream language, it's likely that
        R6 will feel very natural. If not, you may prefer S3 <em>first</em>,
        since R6 will be harder to follow.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-r6-classes">
      <title>Classes and methods</title>

      <p>
        R6 only needs a single function call to create both the class and its
        methods: <c>R6::R6Class()</c>. This is the only function from the
        package that you'll ever use!
      </p>
    </section>

  </chapter>
